Let $\mu$ be a measure on $X$, and let $f:X ightarrow [0,+\infty]$ be $\mu$-measurable. Define the measure: $$ 
u(K) = \int_K f \, d\mu $$ I know that any $\mu$-measurable function $g:X ightarrow [0,+\infty]$ is also $
u$-measurable. I want to show that for any such function, we have: $$ \int g \, d
u = \int g \cdot f \, d\mu $$ I have already proven the case where $g$ is simple. I have also proven that if $h$ is simple, then $h \leq g \;$ $
u$-a.e. if and only if $hf \leq gf \; \mu$-a.e. Using these facts and the definition of the lower integral, we can write:  egin{align*} \int g \, d
u  &= \sup \left\{ \int h \, d
u : h 	ext{ is } 
u 	ext{-integrable, simple, } h \leq g \; 
u 	ext{-a.e.} ight\} \ &= \sup \left\{ \int h \cdot f \, d\mu : h 	ext{ is } 
u 	ext{-integrable, simple, } hf \leq gf \; \mu 	ext{-a.e.} ight\} \end{align*} But at this point I'm lost as to how to transform this into the lower integral of $\int gf \, d\mu$, i.e.: $$ \sup \left\{ \int h \, d\mu : h 	ext{ is } 
u 	ext{-integrable, simple, } h \leq gf \; \mu 	ext{-a.e.} ight\} $$

